# Nova — Cross-Device AI Assistant & Orchestrator

Nova is a personal daily-driver, cross-device AI assistant orchestrator built to coordinate desktop system controls, Android services, and smart home automations from a centralized, secure Python hub.

---

## 🛠️ Tech Stack & Architecture

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph Clients ["Device Clients"]
        CLI[Desktop Client - Python CLI]
        Andr[Android Client - Kotlin Compose]
        Web[Web Dashboard - Glassmorphic SPA]
    end

    subgraph Core ["Nova Core Server"]
        Router[Hybrid AI Router]
        Auth[JWT Token Security Gate]
        Registry[Permission Registry - policy.yaml]
        Engine[Automation Engine]
        DB[(SQLite / PostgreSQL Store)]
    end

    subgraph External ["Services & Fallbacks"]
        CloudLLM[Cloud LLM - Anthropic/OpenRouter/NIM]
        LocalLLM[Local LLM - Ollama]
        Tuya[Tuya Smart Home API]
    end

    CLI <-->|HTTP/WS| Auth
    Andr <-->|HTTP/WS| Auth
    Web <-->|HTTP/WS| Auth

    Auth --> Router
    Router --> Registry
    Registry --> DB
    Engine --> Registry

    Router -->|Cloud Request| CloudLLM
    Router -->|Offline Failover| LocalLLM
    Engine -->|Trigger Commands| Tuya
```

* **Nova Core Server**: Built with FastAPI. Coordinates active contexts, presence status, commands routing, token logins, and automation tick evaluations.
* **Desktop Agent Client**: A thin Python wrapper running actions locally using platform-specific adapters (`psutil`, `pyautogui`, shell).
* **Android Kotlin Client**: Features Jetpack Compose layouts, background keep-alives, Speech-to-Text command triggers, and notification Accessibility Services.
* **Web Dashboard SPA**: Serves a dark-themed glassmorphism console layout showing metrics, live WebSocket log outputs, and rule configuration forms.

---

## 🔑 How to Set AI API Keys

Configuration parameters are loaded from a `.env` file at the root of the workspace directory. Run the `setup.bat` script to automatically scaffold the file, and then edit the following keys:

### 1. Anthropic API (Default)
```env
LLM_PROVIDER=anthropic
LLM_API_KEY=sk-ant-api53-xxx...
LLM_MODEL=claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022
```

### 2. OpenRouter API
```env
LLM_PROVIDER=openrouter
LLM_API_KEY=sk-or-v1-xxx...
LLM_API_BASE=https://openrouter.ai/api/v1
LLM_MODEL=anthropic/claude-3.5-sonnet
```

### 3. NVIDIA NIM API
```env
LLM_PROVIDER=nvidia
LLM_API_KEY=nvapi-xxx...
LLM_API_BASE=https://integrate.api.nvidia.com/v1
LLM_MODEL=meta/llama-3.1-405b-instruct
```

### 4. Local Ollama Fallback (Offline Mode)
If cloud requests fail or the device goes offline, Nova automatically falls back to your local Ollama instance:
```env
LOCAL_LLM_URL=http://localhost:11434/v1
LOCAL_LLM_MODEL=llama3
```

---

## 🚀 Quick Start (Windows)

### 1. Run Setup Script
Run the automated environment batch script to build a virtual environment, install package dependencies in editable mode, and create a default `.env`:
```bash
setup.bat
```

### 2. Configure Credentials
Open `.env` and set your preferred `ADMIN_PASSWORD` (defaults to `nayakacode`), `LLM_PROVIDER`, and `LLM_API_KEY`.

### 3. Launch Nova Core Server
Start the centralized Python hub:
```bash
python -m nova_core.main
```
The server will boot on `http://127.0.0.1:8000`. You can access the **Web Dashboard** by navigating to this address in your web browser.

### 4. Launch Desktop Agent Client
In another terminal session, launch the CLI client:
```bash
python -m desktop_agent.main
```

---

## 🔒 Security & Policy Engine (`policy.yaml`)

Both the Core server and client agents validate action requests against a local `policy.yaml` configuration.
* **unconditional floor**: Shell execution commands (`run_script`, `install_package`) always require explicit verification prompts (`always_explicit`), even if configured as `none` in files.
* **whitelisted actions**: Read-only stats (`get_battery`) or local whitelisted apps (`notepad`) execute silently, while others request console confirmations.

---

## 🧪 Running Tests

Ensure all automated tests pass by executing pytest inside the virtual environment:
```bash
python -m pytest
```
